  "prompt": "What is Fiverr, and how do they make money?",
  "response": "Fiverr is an online marketplace that allows freelancers to offer their services to customers worldwide. Founded in 2010, Fiverr initially started as a platform where freelancers could offer services (called \"gigs\") starting at $5. Over the years, it has expanded to include a wide range of services across various categories, such as graphic design, writing and translation, video editing, programming, digital marketing, and more.\n\n### How Fiverr Makes Money:\n\n1. **Service Fees**: Fiverr charges freelancers a percentage fee on each transaction. Typically, this fee is around 20% of the earnings from a completed order. So, if a freelancer sells a gig for $100, Fiverr will take $20 as a fee.\n\n2. **Buyer Fees**: Fiverr also charges buyers a service fee on top of the purchase price. This fee varies based on the cost of the gig. For example, there might be a fixed fee for smaller purchases and a percentage fee for larger ones.\n\n3. **Fiverr Pro**: Fiverr offers a premium service called Fiverr Pro, which features top-tier freelancers who are vetted for quality. Listings in Fiverr Pro may command higher prices, and Fiverr may take a larger commission on these services.\n\n4. **Fiverr Business**: This is a subscription service tailored for companies looking to hire freelancers. Businesses pay a subscription fee for access to a curated selection of freelancers and additional features, generating recurring revenue.\n\n5. **Promoted Gigs**: Freelancers can pay to promote their gigs to enhance their visibility on the platform. This means Fiverr generates revenue from advertising features that freelancers choose to utilize.\n\n6. **Add-Ons and Extras**: Many freelancers offer add-ons or premium versions of their services, which can increase the overall value of a transaction, leading to higher fees for Fiverr.\n\nBy leveraging these various revenue streams, Fiverr has successfully established itself as a leading platform for freelance services globally.",
